body:
Using node hydration could make this code more clear, concise in my opinion.

```suggestion
		it("delete multiple rows", () => {
			const { treeView } = createTableTree();
			const row0 = new Row({ id: "row-0", cells: {} });
			const row1 = new Row({ id: "row-1", cells: {} });
			treeView.initialize({
				columns: [],
				rows: [ row0, row1 ],
			});

			treeView.root.deleteRows([row0, row1]);
			assertEqualTrees(treeView.root, {
				columns: [],
				rows: [],
			});
		});
```

Also I think we should test more cases than just dealing all the rows in order.

A bug where deleteRows deletes too much, or doesn't handle rows which are out of order are both easy bugs to have that this test won't detect.

I think all your tests would pass if deleteRows deleted every row no matter what you passed, or if it deleted rows incorrectly index backwards from the end for example.

Maybe add a case to the "delete single row" case where there is more than one row and it deletes one of them.

Consider also a case for "delete multiple rows" where you delete things out of order such that that computing the indexes then deleting them would error. Ex: have rows [0, 1, 2, 3] then try removing 0 and 2 and ensure that works, as well as removing 2 and 0.

